<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06094202 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06094202 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION; SUPPORT; US; VETERAN; MIDEAST; WAR  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Sensitive Democrat Alan Alda, macho Republican Charlton Heston and a raft ofother celebrities have signed up for a TV welcome-home extravaganza forPersian Gulf war veterans tonight.;    The two-hour &quot;All-Star Salute to OurTroops&quot; airs on CBS from a huge airplane hangar at Andrews Air Force Base inMaryland. President Bush is planning to attend the show and make brief remarks.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TV'S 'SALUTE' INVITES GUESTS OF ALL STRIPES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Turmoil in the MideastSee also related article on page 1A and 6A of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     An audience of 4,000, including Bush and his family along with returnedtroops and foreign dignitaries, will be treated to an eclectic roster ofentertainers chosen at least in part for their diverse political leanings.;   Heston, Sophia Loren and Richard Thomas will be hosts for the broadcast.Country music, Bush's favorite, is heavily represented by singers BarbaraMandrell, Randy Travis, Gary Morris and Ray Stevens.;    Veteran actor GlennFord will be on hand as will various military musical groups and a choir of 25Kuwaiti-born children singing the U.S. national anthem.;    The show, one ofseveral planned or already aired by various networks to honor the troops, isthe brainchild of Roger Ailes, a producer and GOP media consultant best-knownfor the biting commercials that helped put Bush in the White House.;    CBS ispaying for the show, and Ailes is co-producing it with Gary Smith, whoproduced the 1988 Democratic National Convention for TV. Both say there isnothing partisan about this project.; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The show will bebroadcast at 8 p.m. today on Channels 5, 10 and 46.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </C